esent)</small>\n* [[KLC]] <small>(1995\u2013present)</small>\n* [[Mo B. Dick]] <small>(1995\u2013present)</small>\n* [[Odell (producer)|O'Dell]] <small>(1995\u2013present)</small>\n\n;Former members\n* Tre-8 <small>(1995)</small> \n* [[Carlos Stephens]] <small>(1995\u20131999)</small>\n* Ken \"K-Lou\" Franklin <small>(1995\u20131997)</small>\n* [[DJ Daryl]] <small>(1996\u20131998)</small>\n* Elvin \u201cPlaya Pizzle\u201d Presley <small>(2006\u20132016)</small>\n* Richard Weber <small>(2006\u20132009)</small>\n* C.Smith <small>(2006\u20132009)</small>\n* DJ Don Juan <small>(2006\u20132010)</small>\n* Tic Toc <small>(2006\u20132009)</small>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{No Limit Records}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Medicine Men}}\n[[Category:American hip hop groups]]\n[[Category:Southern hip hop groups]]\n[[Category:Tommy Boy Records artists]]\n[[Category:No Limit Records artists]]\n[[Category:American hip hop record producers]]\n[[Category:Record production teams]]\n", "name_user": "Nihiltres", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Standardized hatnote", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Medicine_Men"}
{"title_page": "Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Salerno-Campagna-Acerno", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=January 2017}}\n{{Infobox diocese\n| jurisdiction      = Archdiocese<!-- Type of jurisdiction: i.e. Diocese or Archdiocese -->\n| name              = Salerno-Campagna-Acerno\n| latin             = Archidioecesis Salernitana-Campaniensis-Acernensis\n| local             = <!-- Name in the native language --> \n| image             = Salerno 2013-05-17 09-37-10.jpg\n| image_size        =  \n| image_alt         = \n| caption           = [[Salerno]] Cathedral\n<!---- Locations ---->\n| country           = [[Italy]]\n| metropolitan      =  \n| territory         = \n| province          = Salerno-Campagna-Acerno\n| coordinates       = <!-- Use {{coord}} --> \n<!---- Statistics ---->\n| area_km2          = 1,398\n| population        = 552,000\n| population_as_of  = 2010\n| catholics         = 540,000<!-- Number of Catholics in the diocese -->\n| catholics_percent = 97.8\n| parishes          = 163<!-- Number of parishes in the diocese -->\n| churches          = <!-- Number of churches in the diocese -->\n| congregations     = <!-- Number of congregations in the diocese -->\n| schools           = <!-- Number of church supported schools in the diocese -->\n| members           = <!-- Number of members in the diocese -->\n<!---- Information ---->\n| denomination      = [[Catholic Church]]\n| rite              = [[Roman Rite]]\n| established       = 6th century\n| cathedral         = [[Salerno Cathedral|Cattedrale-Basilica di S. Matteo]] (Salerno)\n| cocathedral       = Concattedrale-Basilica di S. Maria della Pace (Campagna)<br>[[Acerno Cathedral|Concattedrale di S. Donato]] (Acerno)\n| patron            = \n| priests           = <!-- Number of priests in the diocese -->\n<!---- Current leadership ---->\n| pope              = {{Incumbent pope}} <!-- DO NOT CHANGE. This will update the Popes Automatically as they change -->\n| bishop_title      = Archbishop\n| bishop            = [[Luigi Moretti (archbishop)|Luigi Moretti]]\n| coadjutor         = \n| auxiliary_bishops = \n| vicar_general     = \n| emeritus_bishops  = [[Gerardo Pierro]]\n<!---- Map ---->\n| map               = \n| map_alt           = \n| map_caption       = \n<!---- Website ---->\n| website           = [http://www.diocesisalerno.it/ www.diocesisalerno.it]\n| footnotes         = \n|coat=|flag=|headquarters=|sui_iuris_church=|founded=|dissolved=|language=}}\n{{multiple images\n|footer=Co-cathedral in [[Campagna]] (left) Co-cathedral in [[Acerno]]\n|image1=Cattedrale Campagna.JPG\n|width1=250\n|image2=Concattedrale acerno.jpg\n|width2=142\n}}\nThe '''Archdiocese of Salerno-Campagna-Acerno''' ({{lang-la|Archidioecesis Salernitana-Campaniensis-Acernensis}}) is a Roman Catholic ecclesiastical territory in [[Campania]], southern Italy, created in 1986. The historic '''Archdiocese of Salerno''' was in existence from the tenth century, having been elevated from a sixth-century diocese. The [[Diocese of Acerno]] was combined with the archdiocese in 1818.<ref name=CathHierSalerno>[http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/diocese/dscai.html \"Archdiocese of Salerno-Campagna-Acerno\"] ''[[Catholic-Hierarchy.org]].'' David M. Cheney. Retrieved February 29, 2016</ref><ref name=GCathSalerno>[http://www.gcatholic.org/dioceses/diocese/sale0.htm \"Metropolitan Archdiocese of Salerno\u2013Campagna\u2013Acerno\"] ''GCatholic.org.'' Gabriel Chow. Retrieved February 29, 2016</ref>\n\nOn Thursday, June 10, 2010, [[Pope Benedict XVI]] appointed Archbishop [[Luigi Moretti (archbishop)|Luigi Moretti]], until then the vice-gerent of the Vicariate of Rome, as Archbishop, succeeding Archbishop [[Gerardo Pierro]].\n\n==History==\n\nGaudentius was bishop in 499. Other bishops were: Asterius, who went to Constantinople with [[Pope Agapetus I|Pope Agapitus]] in 534; St Gaudiosus (eighth century); Petrus (834), formerly [[Bishop of Canusio]], who took refuge at Salerno when the Saracens destroyed his capital, and built the Church of San Giovanni Battista; Bernardus (850), who restored several buildings.\n\nIn the eighth century the city of [[Salerno]] was in the power of the Lombard [[dukes of Benevento]]. In 984 Salerno became an archiepiscopal see, the first archbishop being Amato. Other archbishops were:\n\n*[[San Alfano]] (1058\u201385), who received the exiled [[Pope Gregory VII]]\n*[[Romuald I (Archbishop of Salerno)|Romualdo I]] (1121)\n*[[Romuald Guarna|Romualdo II Guarna]] (1153)\n*[[Nicolo Agello]] (1181)\n*[[Caesarius of Alagno]] (1225\u201363)\n*[[Guglielmo de' Godoni]] (1298), chancellor of the Duke of Calabria, whose successors, to [[Orso Minutolo]] (1330), resided at Avignon\n*[[Barnaba Orsini]] (1441), who restored the cathedral\n*[[Pietro Guglielmo Rocca]] (d. 1482)\n*[[Juan de Vera|Giovanni Vera]] (1500), later a cardinal, who was sent on several pontifical legations to France and to England\n*[[Girolamo Seripando]] (1554), theologian and former general of the Augustinians, whose doctrines on [[Justification (theology)|justification]], akin to those of Luther, were rejected at the [[Council of Trent]], and who afterwards became a cardinal\n*[[Gaspar Cervantes de Gaeta]] (1564), who founded the seminary\n*[[Marc Antonio Colonna]] (1568), who established another college for clerics\n*his nephew, [[Marc Antonio Colonna]] (1574), the author\n*[[Mario Bolognini]] (1591), who distinguished himself in France in the controversies with the [[Huguenots]]; \n*[[Giovanni de Torres]] (1658), who reformed the lives of the clergy; \n*[[Gregorio Caraffa]] (1664), a [[Theatine]] and reformer; \n*[[Antonio Salomone]], who, after the annexation of the kingdom of Naples, was imprisoned without reason (1886), and at the beginning of the war with Austria was sent into exile.\n\nFrom 1818 Salerno had for suffragans the [[diocese of Capaccio e Vallo]], [[diocese of Policastro]], [[diocese of Potenza e Marsico Nuovo]], and [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Nusco|diocese of Nusco]].\n\nThe See of Acerno, which appears a diocese since 1136, is united with it; among its bishops was the Franciscan [[Antonio Bonito]] (1493).\\\n\n==Ordinaries==\n===Diocese of Salerno===\n''Latin Name: Salernitana''<br>\n''Erected: 6th Century''\n\n===Archdiocese of Salerno===\n''Latin Name: Salernitana''<br>\n''Elevated: 10th Century''\n\n*[[Romualdo Guarna]] (1121 Appointed \u2013 21 Jan 1136 Died)\n:'''...'''\n*[[Bertrand de La Tour]], [[Order of Friars Minor|O.F.M.]] (3 Sep 1320 Appointed \u2013 30 Apr 1321 Resigned)\n*[[Arnaud Royardi]], [[Order of Friars Minor|O.F.M.]] (30 Apr 1321 Appointed \u2013 27 Jun 1330 Appointed, Archbishop (Personal Title) of Sarlat)\n:'''...'''\n*[[Bertrand de Castronovo]] (de Chateauneuf) (7 Jan 1349 Appointed \u2013 8 Jan 1364 Appointed, [[Ancient Diocese of Embrun|Archbishop of Embrun]])\n:'''...'''\n*[[Nicola Piscicelli]] (21 Apr 1449 Appointed \u2013 Apr 1471 Died)\n*[[Pietro Guglielmo de Rocha]] (30 Aug 1471 Appointed \u2013 18 Oct 1482 Died)\n*[[Giovanni d'Aragona (cardinal)|Giovanni d'Aragona]] (13 Jan 1483 Appointed \u2013 17 Oct 1485 Died)\n*[[Juan de Vera]] (10 Jul 1500 Appointed \u2013 4 May 1507 Died)\n*[[Federico Freg\u00f3so]] (5 May 1507 Appointed \u2013 1529 Resigned)\n*[[Niccol\u00f2 Ridolfi]] (7 Feb 1533 Appointed \u2013 19 Dec 1548 Resigned)\n*[[Luis Torres (bishop)]] (19 Dec 1548 Appointed \u2013 13 Aug 1553 Died)\n*[[Girolamo Seripando]], [[O.E.S.A.]] (30 Mar 1554 Appointed \u2013 17 Apr 1563 Died)\n*[[Gaspar Cervantes de Gaeta]] (1 Mar 1564 Appointed \u2013 23 Jul 1568 Appointed, [[Archbishop of Tarragona]])\n*[[Marcantonio Colonna (seniore)]] (13 Oct 1568 Appointed \u2013 25 Jun 1574 Resigned)\n*[[Marco Antonio Marsilio]] (25 Jun 1574 Appointed \u2013 24 Apr 1589 Died)\n*[[Mario Bolognini]] (7 Jan 1591 Appointed \u2013 25 Feb 1605 Died)<ref name=CathHierMarioBolo>[http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/bishop/bbolognm.html \"Archbishop Mario Bolognini\"] ''[[Catholic-Hierarchy.org]]''. David M. Cheney. Retrieved March 21, 2016</ref>\n*[[Juan Beltr\u00e1n Guevara y Figueroa]] (4 Dec 1606 Appointed \u2013 28 Nov 1611 Appointed, [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of M\u00e9rida-Badajoz|Archbishop (Personal Title) of Badajoz]])<ref name=CathHierJuanBeltran>[http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/bishop/bbgyf.html \"Archbishop Juan Beltr\u00e1n Guevara y Figueroa\"] ''[[Catholic-Hierarchy.org]].'' David M. Cheney. Retrieved February 29, 2016</ref>\n*[[Lucio Sanseverino]] (19 Nov 1612 Appointed \u2013 25 Dec 1623 Died)\n*[[Gabriel Trejo y Paniagua]] (9 Jun 1625 Appointed \u2013 12 Feb 1630 Died)\n*[[Giulio Savelli]] (28 Jan 1630 Appointed \u2013 15 Sep 1642 Resigned)\n*[[Fabrizio Savelli]] (15 Sep 1642 Appointed \u2013 1 Apr 1658 Resigned)\n*[[Giovanni de Torres]] (1 Apr 1658 Appointed \u2013 Sep 1662 Died)\n*[[Gregorio Carafa (archbishop)]], [[Theatines|C.R.]] (23 Jun 1664 Confirmed \u2013 22 Feb 1675 Died)\n*[[Alfonso \u00c1lvarez Barba Ossorio]], [[O. Carm.]] (22 Jun 1676 Confirmed \u2013 Oct 1688 Died)\n*[[Gerolamo Passarelli]] (14 Nov 1689 Appointed \u2013 Nov 1690 Died)\n*[[Marcos de Ostos]], [[O. de M.]] (25 Jun 1692 Appointed \u2013 19 Nov 1695 Died)\n*[[Bonaventura Poerio]], [[O.F.M. Obs.]] (11 Nov 1697 Appointed \u2013 18 Nov 1722 Died)\n*Pablo Vilana Perlas (12 May 1723 Confirmed \u2013 6 May 1729 Died)\n*Giovanni Fabrizio de Capua (11 Dec 1730 Confirmed \u2013 1 Mar 1738 Died)\n*Casimiro Rossi (5 May 1738 Appointed \u2013 27 Dec 1758 Died)\n*Isidoro S\u00e1nchez de Luna, [[Order of Saint Benedict|O.S.B.]] (28 May 1759 Confirmed \u2013 13 May 1783 Resigned)\n*Giulio (Giovanni Michele) Pignatelli, [[Order of Saint Benedict|O.S.B.]] (25 Jun 1784 Confirmed \u2013 17 Aug 1796 Died)\n*Salvatore Spinelli, [[Order of Saint Benedict|O.S.B.]] (18 Dec 1797 Confirmed \u2013 8 Jan 1805 Died)\n*Fortunado Pinto (26 Jun 1805 Confirmed \u2013 20 Nov 1825 Died)\n\n===Archdiocese of Salerno (-Acerno)===\n''Latin Name: Salernitana (-Acernensis)''<br>\n''United: 27 June 1818 with the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Acerno|Diocese of Acerno]]''\n\n*[[Camillo Alleva]] (19 Dec 1825 Confirmed \u2013 30 Oct 1829 Died)\n*[[Michelangelo Lupoli]] (30 Sep 1831 Confirmed \u2013 28 Jul 1834 Died)\n*[[Marino Paglia]] (6 Apr 1835 Confirmed \u2013 5 Sep 1857 Died)\n*[[Antonio Salomone]] (21 Dec 1857 Confirmed \u2013 9 Mar 1872 Died)\n*[[Domenico Guadalupi]] (6 May 1872 Appointed \u2013 8 Mar 1877 Resigned)\n*[[Valerio Laspro]] (20 Mar 1877 Appointed \u2013 22 Sep 1914 Died)\n*[[Carlo Gregorio Maria Grasso]], O.S.B. (7 Apr 1915 Appointed \u2013 30 Mar 1929 Died)\n*[[Nicola Monterisi]] (5 Oct 1929 Appointed \u2013 30 Mar 1944 Died)\n*[[Demetrio Moscato]] (22 Jan 1945 Appointed \u2013 22 Oct 1968 Died)\n*[[Gaetano Pollio]], P.I.M.E. (5 Feb 1969 Appointed \u2013 20 Oct 1984 Resigned)\n*[[Guerino Grimaldi]] (20 Oct 1984 Succeeded \u2013 12 Apr 1992 Died)\n\n===Archdiocese of Salerno-Campagna-Acerno===\n''Latin Name: Salernitana-Campaniensis-Acernensis<br>\n''United: 30 September 1986 with the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Campagna|Diocese of Campagna]]''\n\n*[[Gerardo Pierro]] (25 May 1992 Appointed \u2013 10 Jun 2010 Retired)\n*[[Luigi Moretti (archbishop)|Luigi Moretti]] (10 Jun 2010 Appointed \u2013 )\n\n==See also==\n* [[School of Salerno]]\n* [[Timeline of Salerno]]\n\n==Notes==\n<references/>\n\n==Bibliography==\n*Cappelletti, ''Le Chiese d'Italia'', XX (Venice, 1857);\n\n==External links==\n* {{Catholic-hierarchy|diocese|dscai|Archdiocese of Salerno-Campagna-Acerno}}\n\n{{Catholic Encyclopedia|wstitle=Archdiocese of Salerno-Campagna-Acerno}}\n\n{{Roman Catholic Ecclesiastical Province of Salerno-Campagna-Acerno}}\n\n{{coord|40.6833|N|14.7667|E|source:wikidata-and-enwiki-cat-tree_region:IT|display=title}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Salerno}}\n[[Category:Roman Catholic dioceses in Campania]]\n[[Category:Dioceses established in the 6th century]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=January 2017}}\n{{Infobox diocese\n| jurisdiction      = Archdiocese<!-- Type of jurisdiction: i.e. Diocese or Archdiocese -->\n| name              = Salerno-Campagna-Acerno\n| latin             = Archidioecesis Salernitana-Campaniensis-Acernensis\n| local             = <!-- Name in the native language --> \n| image             = Salerno 2013-05-17 09-37-10.jpg\n| image_size        =  \n| image_alt         = \n| caption           = [[Salerno]] Cathedral\n<!---- Locations ---->\n| country           = [[Italy]]\n| metropolitan      =  \n| territory         = \n| province          = Salerno-Campagna-Acerno\n| coordinates       = <!-- Use {{coord}} --> \n<!---- Statistics ---->\n| area_km2          = 1,398\n| population        = 552,000\n| population_as_of  = 2010\n| catholics         = 540,000<!-- Number of Catholics in the diocese -->\n| catholics_percent = 97.8\n| parishes          = 163<!-- Number of parishes in the diocese -->\n| churches          = <!-- Number of churches in the diocese -->\n| congregations     = <!-- Number of congregations in the diocese -->\n| schools           = <!-- Number of church supported schools in the diocese -->\n| members           = <!-- Number of members in the diocese -->\n<!---- Information ---->\n| denomination      = [[Catholic Church]]\n| rite              = [[Roman Rite]]\n| established       = 6th century\n| cathedral         = [[Salerno Cathedral|Cattedrale-Basilica di S. Matteo]] (Salerno)\n| cocathedral       = Concattedrale-Basilica di S. Maria della Pace (Campagna)<br>[[Acerno Cathedral|Concattedrale di S. Donato]] (Acerno)\n| patron            = \n| priests           = <!-- Number of priests in the diocese -->\n<!---- Current leadership ---->\n| pope              = {{Incumbent pope}} <!-- DO NOT CHANGE. This will update the Popes Automatically as they change -->\n| bishop_title      = Archbishop\n| bishop            = [[Luigi Moretti (archbishop)|Luigi Moretti]]\n| coadjutor         = \n| auxiliary_bishops = \n| vicar_general     = \n| emeritus_bishops  = [[Gerardo Pierro]]\n<!---- Map ---->\n| map               = \n| map_alt           = \n| map_caption       = \n<!---- Website ---->\n| website           = [http://www.diocesisalerno.it/ www.diocesisalerno.it]\n| footnotes         = \n|coat=|flag=|headquarters=|sui_iuris_church=|founded=|dissolved=|language=}}\n{{multiple images\n|footer=Co-cathedral in [[Campagna]] (left) Co-cathedral in [[Acerno]]\n|image1=Cattedrale Campagna.JPG\n|width1=250\n|image2=Concattedrale acerno.jpg\n|width2=142\n}}\nThe '''Archdiocese of Salerno-Campagna-Acerno''' ({{lang-la|Archidioecesis Salernitana-Campaniensis-Acernensis}}) is a Roman Catholic ecclesiastical territory in [[Campania]], southern Italy, created in 1986. The historic '''Archdiocese of Salerno''' was in existence from the tenth century, having been elevated from a sixth-century diocese. The [[Diocese of Acerno]] was combined with the archdiocese in 1818.<ref name=CathHierSalerno>[http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/diocese/dscai.html \"Archdiocese of Salerno-Campagna-Acerno\"] ''[[Catholic-Hierarchy.org]].'' David M. Cheney. Retrieved February 29, 2016</ref><ref name=GCathSalerno>[http://www.gcatholic.org/dioceses/diocese/sale0.htm \"Metropolitan Archdiocese of Salerno\u2013Campagna\u2013Acerno\"] ''GCatholic.org.'' Gabriel Chow. Retrieved February 29, 2016</ref>\n\nOn Thursday, June 10, 2010, [[Pope Benedict XVI]] appointed Archbishop [[Luigi Moretti (archbishop)|Luigi Moretti]], until then the vice-gerent of the Vicariate of Rome, as Archbishop, succeeding Archbishop [[Gerardo Pierro]].\n\n==History==\n\nGaudentius was bishop in 499. Other bishops were: Asterius, who went to Constantinople with [[Pope Agapetus I|Pope Agapitus]] in 534; St Gaudiosus (eighth century); Petrus (834), formerly [[Bishop of Canusio]], who took refuge at Salerno when the Saracens destroyed his capital, and built the Church of San Giovanni Battista; Bernardus (850), who restored several buildings.\n\nIn the eighth century the city of [[Salerno]] was in the power of the Lombard [[dukes of Benevento]]. In 984 Salerno became an archiepiscopal see, the first archbishop being Amato. Other archbishops were:\n\n*[[San Alfano]] (1058\u201385), who received the exiled [[Pope Gregory VII]]\n*[[Romuald I (Archbishop of Salerno)|Romualdo I]] (1121)\n*[[Romuald Guarna|Romualdo II Guarna]] (1153)\n*[[Nicolo Agello]] (1181)\n*[[Caesarius of Alagno]] (1225\u201363)\n*[[Guglielmo de' Godoni]] (1298), chancellor of the Duke of Calabria, whose successors, to [[Orso Minutolo]] (1330), resided at Avignon\n*[[Barnaba Orsini]] (1441), who restored the cathedral\n*[[Pietro Guglielmo Rocca]] (d. 1482)\n*[[Juan de Vera|Giovanni Vera]] (1500), later a cardinal, who was sent on several pontifical legations to France and to England\n*[[Girolamo Seripando]] (1554), theologian and former general of the Augustinians, whose doctrines on [[Justification (theology)|justification]], akin to those of Luther, were rejected at the [[Council of Trent]], and who afterwards became a cardinal\n*[[Gaspar Cervantes de Gaeta]] (1564), who founded the seminary\n*[[Marc Antonio Colonna]] (1568), who established another college for clerics\n*his nephew, [[Marc Antonio Colonna]] (1574), the author\n*[[Mario Bolognini]] (1591), who distinguished himself in France in the controversies with the [[Huguenots]]; \n*[[Giovanni de Torres]] (1658), who reformed the lives of the clergy; \n*[[Gregorio Caraffa]] (1664), a [[Theatine]] and reformer; \n*[[Antonio Salomone]], who, after the annexation of the kingdom of Naples, was imprisoned without reason (1886), and at the beginning of the war with Austria was sent into exile.\n\nFrom 1818 Salerno had for suffragans the [[diocese of Capaccio e Vallo]], [[diocese of Policastro]], [[diocese of Potenza e Marsico Nuovo]], and [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Nusco|diocese of Nusco]].\n\nThe See of Acerno, which appears a diocese since 1136, is united with it; among its bishops was the Franciscan [[Antonio Bonito]] (1493).\\\n\n==Ordinaries==\n===Diocese of Salerno===\n''Latin Name: Salernitana''<br>\n''Erected: 6th Century''\n\n===Archdiocese of Salerno===\n''Latin Name: Salernitana''<br>\n''Elevated: 10th Century''\n\n*[[Romualdo Guarna]] (1121 Appointed \u2013 21 Jan 1136 Died)\n:'''...'''\n*[[Bertrand de La Tour]], [[Order of Friars Minor|O.F.M.]] (3 Sep 1320 Appointed \u2013 30 Apr 1321 Resigned)\n*[[Arnaud Royardi]], [[Order of Friars Minor|O.F.M.]] (30 Apr 1321 Appointed \u2013 27 Jun 1330 Appointed, Archbishop (Personal Title) of Sarlat)\n:'''...'''\n*[[Bertrand de Castronovo]] (de Chateauneuf) (7 Jan 1349 Appointed \u2013 8 Jan 1364 Appointed, [[Ancient Diocese of Embrun|Archbishop of Embrun]])\n:'''...'''\n*[[Nicola Piscicelli]] (21 Apr 1449 Appointed \u2013 Apr 1471 Died)\n*[[Pietro Guglielmo de Rocha]] (30 Aug 1471 Appointed \u2013 18 Oct 1482 Died)\n*[[Giovanni d'Aragona (cardinal)|Giovanni d'Aragona]] (13 Jan 1483 Appointed \u2013 17 Oct 1485 Died)\n*[[Juan de Vera]] (10 Jul 1500 Appointed \u2013 4 May 1507 Died)\n*[[Federico Freg\u00f3so]] (5 May 1507 Appointed \u2013 1529 Resigned)\n*[[Niccol\u00f2 Ridolfi]] (7 Feb 1533 Appointed \u2013 19 Dec 1548 Resigned)\n*[[Luis Torres (bishop)]] (19 Dec 1548 Appointed \u2013 13 Aug 1553 Died)\n*[[Girolamo Seripando]], [[O.E.S.A.]] (30 Mar 1554 Appointed \u2013 17 Apr 1563 Died)\n*[[Gaspar Cervantes de Gaeta]] (1 Mar 1564 Appointed \u2013 23 Jul 1568 Appointed, [[Archbishop of Tarragona]])\n*[[Marcantonio Colonna (seniore)]] (13 Oct 1568 Appointed \u2013 25 Jun 1574 Resigned)\n*[[Marco Antonio Marsilio]] (25 Jun 1574 Appointed \u2013 24 Apr 1589 Died)\n*[[Mario Bolognini]] (7 Jan 1591 Appointed \u2013 25 Feb 1605 Died)<ref name=CathHierMarioBolo>[http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/bishop/bbolognm.html \"Archbishop Mario Bolognini\"] ''[[Catholic-Hierarchy.org]]''. David M. Cheney. Retrieved March 21, 2016</ref>\n*[[Juan Beltr\u00e1n Guevara y Figueroa]] (4 Dec 1606 Appointed \u2013 28 Nov 1611 Appointed, [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of M\u00e9rida-Badajoz|Archbishop (Personal Title) of Badajoz]])<ref name=CathHierJuanBeltran>[http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/bishop/bbgyf.html \"Archbishop Juan Beltr\u00e1n Guevara y Figueroa\"] ''[[Catholic-Hierarchy.org]].'' David M. Cheney. Retrieved February 29, 2016</ref>\n*[[Lucio Sanseverino]] (19 Nov 1612 Appointed \u2013 25 Dec 1623 Died)\n*[[Gabriel Trejo y Paniagua]] (9 Jun 1625 Appointed \u2013 12 Feb 1630 Died)\n*[[Giulio Savelli]] (28 Jan 1630 Appointed \u2013 15 Sep 1642 Resigned)\n*[[Fabrizio Savelli]] (15 Sep 1642 Appointed \u2013 1 Apr 1658 Resigned)\n*[[Giovanni de Torres]] (1 Apr 1658 Appointed \u2013 Sep 1662 Died)\n*[[Gregorio Carafa (archbishop)]], [[Theatines|C.R.]] (23 Jun 1664 Confirmed \u2013 22 Feb 1675 Died)\n*[[Alfonso \u00c1lvarez Barba Ossorio]], [[O. Carm.]] (22 Jun 1676 Confirmed \u2013 Oct 1688 Died)\n*[[Gerolamo Passarelli]] (14 Nov 1689 Appointed \u2013 Nov 1690 Died)\n*[[Marcos de Ostos]], [[O. de M.]] (25 Jun 1692 Appointed \u2013 19 Nov 1695 Died)\n*[[Bonaventura Poerio]], [[O.F.M. Obs.]] (11 Nov 1697 Appointed \u2013 18 Nov 1722 Died)\n*Pablo Vilana Perlas (12 May 1723 Confirmed \u2013 6 May 1729 Died)\n*Giovanni Fabrizio de Capua (11 Dec 1730 Confirmed \u2013 1 Mar 1738 Died)\n*Casimiro Rossi (5 May 1738 Appointed \u2013 27 Dec 1758 Died)\n*Isidoro S\u00e1nchez de Luna, [[Order of Saint Benedict|O.S.B.]] (28 May 1759 Confirmed \u2013 13 May 1783 Resigned)\n*Giulio (Giovanni Michele) Pignatelli, [[Order of Saint Benedict|O.S.B.]] (25 Jun 1784 Confirmed \u2013 17 Aug 1796 Died)\n*Salvatore Spinelli, [[Order of Saint Benedict|O.S.B.]] (18 Dec 1797 Confirmed \u2013 8 Jan 1805 Died)\n*Fortunado Pinto (26 Jun 1805 Confirmed \u2013 20 Nov 1825 Died)\n\n===Archdiocese of Salerno (-Acerno)===\n''Latin Name: Salernitana (-Acernensis)''<br>\n''United: 27 June 1818 with the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Acerno|Diocese of Acerno]]''\n\n*[[Camillo Alleva]] (19 Dec 1825 Confirmed \u2013 30 Oct 1829 Died)\n*[[Michelangelo Lupoli]] (30 Sep 1831 Confirmed \u2013 28 Jul 1834 Died)\n*[[Marino Paglia]] (6 Apr 1835 Confirmed \u2013 5 Sep 1857 Died)\n*[[Antonio Salomone]] (21 Dec 1857 Confirmed \u2013 9 Mar 1872 Died)\n*[[Domenico Guadalupi]] (6 May 1872 Appointed \u2013 8 Mar 1877 Resigned)\n*[[Valerio Laspro]] (20 Mar 1877 Appointed \u2013 22 Sep 1914 Died)\n*[[Carlo Gregorio Maria Grasso]], O.S.B. (7 Apr 1915 Appointed \u2013 30 Mar 1929 Died)\n*[[Nicola Monterisi]] (5 Oct 1929 Appointed \u2013 30 Mar 1944 Died)\n*[[Demetrio Moscato]] (22 Jan 1945 Appointed \u2013 22 Oct 1968 Died)\n*[[Gaetano Pollio]], P.I.M.E. (5 Feb 1969 Appointed \u2013 20 Oct 1984 Resigned)\n*[[Guerino Grimaldi]] (20 Oct 1984 Succeeded \u2013 12 Apr 1992 Died)\n\n===Archdiocese of Salerno-Campagna-Acerno===\n''Latin Name: Salernitana-Campaniensis-Acernensis<br>\n''United: 30 September 1986 with the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Campagna|Diocese of Campagna]]''\n\n*[[Gerardo Pierro]] (25 May 1992 Appointed \u2013 10 Jun 2010 Retired)\n*[[Luigi Moretti (archbishop)|Luigi Moretti]] (10 Jun 2010 Appointed \u2013 )\n\n==See also==\n* [[School of Salerno]]\n* [[Timeline of Salerno]]\n\n==Notes==\n<references/>\n\n==Bibliography==\n*Cappelletti, ''Le Chiese d'Italia'', XX (Venice, 1857);\n\n==External links==\n* {{Catholic-hierarchy|diocese|dscai|Archdiocese of Salerno-Campagna-Acerno}}\n\n{{Catholic Encyclopedia|wstitle=Archdiocese of Salerno-Campagna-Acerno}} \n\n\n{{Roman Catholic Ecclesiastical Province of Salerno-Campagna-Acerno}}\n\n{{coord|40.6833|N|14.7667|E|source:wikidata-and-enwiki-cat-tree_region:IT|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Salerno}}\n[[Category:Roman Catholic dioceses in Campania]]\n[[Category:Dioceses established in the 6th century]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roman_Catholic_Archdiocese_of_Salerno-Campagna-Acerno"}
{"title_page": "Z\u0101r", "text_new": "{{redirect|Zaar|the language|Zari language||Zaar (disambiguation)}}\n[[File:Z\u0101r ceremony in hormuz island.jpg|thumb|Z\u0101r ceremony on [[Hormuz Island]]]]\nIn the cultures of the [[Horn of Africa]] and adjacent regions of the [[Middle East]],<ref>\"found in Ethiopia, Eritrea, Djibouti, Somalia, Arabia, south and south-west Iran, Egypt and the Sudan.\"\n{{cite journal | last1 = Natvig | first1 = Richard | year = 1987 | title = Oromos, Slaves, and Zar Spirits: a Contribution to the History of the Zar Cults | url = | journal = The International Journal of African Historical Studies | volume = 20 | issue = 4| pages = 647\u2013668 | doi=10.2307/219657| jstor = 219657 }}</ref> \n'''''Z\u0101r''''' ({{lang-ar|\u0632\u0627\u0631}}, {{lang-gez|\u12db\u122d}}) is the term for a [[demon]] or spirit assumed to [[spirit possession|possess]]  individuals, mostly women, and to cause discomfort or illness.\nThe so-called ''z\u0101r'' ritual or ''z\u0101r'' cult is the practice of [[exorcism|exorcising]] such spirits from the possessed individual.<ref name=\"EDD\">{{cite book|last=Guiley|first=Rosemary Ellen|authorlink=Rosemary Ellen Guiley|title=The Encyclopedia of Demons and Demonology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NHosWhaeWDQC&pg=PA277|year=2009|publisher=Infobase Publishing|isbn=978-1-4381-3191-7|page=277}}</ref>\n\n''Z\u0101r'' exorcism has become popular in the contemporary urban culture of [[Cairo]] and other major cities of the Islamic world as a form of women-only entertainment. ''Z\u0101r'' gatherings involve food and musical performances, and they culminate in ecstatic dancing, lasting between three and seven nights.<ref name=\"EDD\"/> \nThe ''[[tanb\u016bra (lyre)|tanb\u016bra]]'', a six-string [[lyre]] (6-stringed \"bowl-lyre\"<ref>Makris 2000, p. 52</ref>), is often used in the ritual.<ref name=\"grove\">{{NewGrove2001|article=Tanb\u016bra|last=Poch\u00e9|first=Christian|vol=xxv|pages=62\u201363}}</ref> Other instruments include the ''[[manjur (instrument)|manjur]]'', a leather belt sewn with many [[goat]] hooves, and various [[percussion instrument]]s.<ref name=\"grove\" />\n\n==History==\nScholarship in the early 20th century attributed Abyssinian (Ethiopian) origin to the custom, although there\nwere also proposals suggesting Persian or other origins.\nThus, [[Leo Frobenius|Frobenius]] suggested that '' z\u0101r'' and ''[[Hausa Animism|bori]]'', a comparable cult in [[Hausa people|Hausa]] culture, were ultimately derived from a Persian source. Modarressi (1986) suggests a Persian etymology for the term.<ref>Taghi Modarressi, \"The Zar Cult in South Iran,\" in R. Prince, ed., Trance and Possession States, Montreal, 1986, pp. 149-55.</ref>\n\nThe origin of the word is unclear; Walker (1935) suggested the name of the city of [[Zara, Iran (disambiguation)|Zara]] in northern Iran, or alternatively the Arabic root ''[[:wikt:\u0632\u0627\u0631#Verb|z-w-r]]'' \"to visit\" (for the possessing spirit \"visiting\" the victim). The ''[[Encyclopedia of Islam]]'' of 1934 favoured an Ethiopian origin of the word.<ref name=\"auto\">cited after Fakhouri (1968), p. 49.</ref>\n\nThe spread beyond the Horn of Africa likely dates to the 18th or early 19th century, presumably introduced by Ethiopian slaves brought to the [[harem]]s of the Ottoman [[Egypt Eyalet]].<ref name=\"auto\"/>\nMessing (1958) states that the cult was particularly well-developed in Northern Ethiopia ([[Amhara Region|Amhara]]), with its center in the town of [[Gondar]].\nOne late 19th-century traveler describes the Abyssinian \"S\u00e1r\" cultists sacrificing a hen or goat and mixing the blood with grease and butter, in the hopes of eliminating someone's sickness.  The concoction was then hidden in an alley, in the belief that all who pass through the alley would take away the patient's ailment.<ref>William Cornwallis Harris, ''The Highlands of Aethiopia,'' volume 2, p. 291</ref>\n\nMirzai Asl (2002) suggests that the introduction to  Iran likewise took place in the 19th century ([[Qajar dynasty|Qajar period]]) by Africans brought to Iran via the [[Arab slave trade]].<ref>Behnaz A. Mirzai Asl, \"African Presence in Iran: Identity and its Reconstruction in the 19th and 20th Centuries,\" Revue fran\u00e7aise d'histoire d'Outre Mer 89, 2002, pp. 229-46.</ref> \nNatvig (1988) reports that the ''z\u0101r'' cult \"served as a refuge for women and effeminate men\" in the [[Sudan (region)|Sahel (Sudan) region]] under [[Islamization of the Sudan region|Islamic rule]].<ref name=numen>{{Citation|last=Natvig|first=Richard|title=Liminal Rites and Female Symbolism in the Egyptian Zar Possession Cult|journal=Numen|volume=35|issue=1|date=July 1988|pages=57\u201368|doi=10.2307/3270140|jstor=3270140}}</ref>\n\n==Varieties ==\nAmong extant varieties of Z\u0101r cults are \"''z\u0101r Saw\u0101kn\u012b'' (the ''z\u0101r'' from the area of [[Suakin]] [\"''Dal\u016bka'', that is, ''z\u0101r Saw\u0101kn\u012b''\"<ref>Makris 2000, p. 141</ref>]) and ''z\u0101r Nyam\u0101nyam'' {cf. /NYAMe/ ('Friend'), god of the Akan} (the ''z\u0101r'' of the [[Azande]])\":<ref>Makris 2000, p. 12</ref> \"the Nyam-Nyam have ''z\u0101r nug\u0101ra'', with Bab\u012bnga and Nak\u016brma\". \"Bab\u012bnga and Nak\u016brma are recognized as Azande ancestral spirits\". Nug\u0101ra (big drum) = \"''nuqara'' ... of the Dega tribe ... was originally from Wau\".<ref>Makris 2000, p. 64</ref> (Wau is in Equatoria province of Sudan.) \"Besides the nug\u0101ra of the Azande, other z\u0101r cults mentioned were those of the Fart\u012bt [Fart\u012bt peoples include \"the Karra, Gula, Feroge, and Surro\"<ref>Makris p. 222, n. 5:15</ref>], the [[Shilluk people]], and the [[Dinka people]] and the ''dinia'' [[Nuba peoples|Nuba]] cult\".<ref>Makris 2000, pp. 64-65</ref>\n\n==Spirits==\nIn Ethiopia, ''z\u0101r'' is used as a term for malevolent spirits or demons.   At the same time, many Ethiopians believe in benevolent, protective spirits, or ''abdar''.<ref name=\"turner\">Turner, John W. Ethiopian Orthodox Christianity: Faith and Practices. ''[http://memory.loc.gov/frd/cs/ettoc.html A Country Study: Ethiopia]''. Thomas P. Ofcansky and LaVerle Berry, eds. Washington: Library of Congress Federal Research Division, 1991.</ref>\n\nBelief in such spirits is widespread among both Christians and Muslims.<ref name=\"beckwith\">Beckwith, Carol, Angela Fisher, and Graham Hancock. ''African Ark''. New York: Henry N. Abrams, Inc., 1990.</ref>{{Rp|199}} \nAs is usual in African animism, and in pre-modern folk belief in general, what would be termed mental illness in modern psychiatry is attributed to spirit possession.<ref name=\"kemp\">Kemp, Charles.  \"[http://bearspace.baylor.edu/Charles_Kemp/www/ethiopian_refugees.htm Ethiopians & Eritreans.]\"  ''Refugee Health \u2013 Immigrant Health''.  Waco, TX: Baylor University.</ref>\n''\u0124\u0113\u1e6d'' (\"thread\"<ref>Makris 2000, p. 195</ref>){{huh|date=May 2016}}<!--\u0124 is a letter used to transcribe Esperanto and Chinook--> is a term of for the possessing spirits. ''Tumbura''  is another term.{{huh|date=May 2016}} Named individual ''tumbura'' include: ''Nuba, Banda, Gumuz, Saw\u0101kiniyya, Lamb\u016bn\u0101t, B\u0101b\u016br\u0101t, B\u0101shaw\u0101t, Khaw\u0101j\u0101t''.<ref>Makris 2000, p. 197</ref> Depending on which spirit an individual is possessed by, they will don different costumes, such a traditional loincloth for ''Nuba'', a straw loincloth for ''Bada'', \na red fez for ''B\u0101\u015baw\u0101t'', and a pith-helmet and khaki shorts for ''\u0124aw\u0101j\u0101t''.<ref>Makris 2000, p. 198&ndash;203</ref>\n\nAccording to legend, there are eighty-eight \"S\u00e1roch\", emissaries of evil all under the service of a spirit named \"Warobal Mama\",<ref>William Cornwallis Harris, ''The Highlands of Aethiopia,'' volume 2, p. 269</ref> who dwells in lake Alobar in the [[Menz]] region.<ref>William Cornwallis Harris, ''The Highlands of Aethiopia,'' volume 2, p. 343</ref>\n\nZ\u0101r beliefs are common today even among Ethiopian immigrants to North America, Europe, or Israel. For example, [[Beta Israel]] are often raised with both [[Judaism|Jewish]] and Z\u0101r beliefs, and individuals who believe they house a spirit are bound to attend to it despite other demands. However, ceremonies can be performed by [[shamans]] to persuade a spirit to leave, thus releasing the person from their duties to that spirit.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Edelstein|first1=Monika|title=Lost Tribes and Coffee Ceremonies: Zar Spirit Possession and the Ethno-Religious Identity of Ethiopian Jews in Israel|journal=Journal of Refugee Studies|date=2002|volume=15|issue=2|url=http://webhome.weizmann.ac.il/home/liorg/zar.pdf|accessdate=5 August 2015|doi=10.1093/jrs/15.2.153|pages=153\u2013170}}</ref>\n\nIn southern Iran, ''z\u0101r'' is interpreted as a \"harmful wind\" assumed to cause discomfort or illness. Types of such winds include ''Maturi, \u0160ay\u1e35 \u0160angar, Dingem\u0101ru, Omag\u0101re, Bumaryom, Pepe, B\u0101bur, Bibi,  Namrud''.<ref name=\"EncIr\">\nMaria Sabaye Moghaddam, [http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/zar Z\u0100R], ''[[Encyclopedia Iranica]]'' (2009).</ref> The film ''The African-Baluchi Trance Dance'' is a 2012 film that depicts a variety of ''zar''-related activities in southeastern Iran.<ref>Hegland, Mary Elaine. 2017. Review essay. ''Iranian Studies'' 50.1:169-172.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[Buda (folk religion)]]\n* [[Fann at-Tanbura]]\n* [[Mazaher]]\n* [[Tanb\u016bra (lyre)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n*Lewis, I. (Ioan)  M.  1991.  Zar in context: The past, the present and future of an African healing cult.  In I. M. Lewis, A. Al-Safi, & S. Hurreiz (Eds.), ''Women's medicine: The Zar Bori cult in Africa and Beyond'' (pp.&nbsp;1\u201316).  Edinburgh, U.K.:  Edinburgh University Press.\n\n{{cleanup-references|date=May 2016}}<!--random literature dump-->\n\n;Ethiopia\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Arieli | first1 = A. | la