irit at | pmid=7926995 | volume=126 | issue=11 | year=1994 | journal=Harefuah | pages=636\u201342, 692| last1=Arieli | first1=A. | last2=Aychen | first2=S. }}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zar}}\n[[Category:Exorcism]]\n[[Category:Demons]]\n[[Category:Jinn]]\n[[Category:Occult]]\n[[Category:Islamic mythology]]\n[[Category:Religion in Djibouti]]\n[[Category:Religion in Egypt]]\n[[Category:Religion in Eritrea]]\n[[Category:Religion in Ethiopia]]\n[[Category:Religion in Somalia]]\n[[Category:Religion in Sudan]]\n", "name_user": "Nihiltres", "label": "safe", "comment": "Standardized hatnote", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Z%C4%81r"}
{"title_page": "Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Reggio Calabria-Bova", "text_new": "{{Infobox diocese\n| jurisdiction      = Archdiocese<!-- Type of jurisdiction: i.e. Diocese or Archdiocese -->\n| name              = Reggio Calabria-Bova\n| latin             = Archidioecesis Rheginensis-Bovensis\n| local             = <!-- Name in the native language --> \n| image             = Il prospetto principale del duomo.jpg\n| image_size        = 255px\n| image_alt         = \n| caption           = [[Reggio Calabria]] Cathedral\n<!---- Locations ---->\n| country           = [[Italy]]\n| metropolitan      =  \n| territory         = \n| province          = Reggio Calabria-Bova\n| coordinates       = <!-- Use {{coord}} --> \n<!---- Statistics ---->\n| area_km2          = 1,004\n| population        = 283,720 (est.)\n| population_as_of  = 2014\n| catholics         = 279,260 (est.)<!-- Number of Catholics in the diocese -->\n| catholics_percent = 98.4\n| parishes          = 119<!-- Number of parishes in the diocese -->\n| churches          = <!-- Number of churches in the diocese -->\n| congregations     = <!-- Number of congregations in the diocese -->\n| schools           = <!-- Number of church supported schools in the diocese -->\n| members           = <!-- Number of members in the diocese -->\n<!---- Information ---->\n| denomination      = [[Catholic Church]]\n| rite              = [[Roman Rite]]\n| established       = 1st century\n| cathedral         = Basilica Cattedrale di Maria SS. Assunta in Cielo (Reggio Calabria)\n| cocathedral       = Concattedrale della Presentazione della Beata Vergine Maria (Bova)\n| patron            = \n| priests           = 119 (diocesan)<br />53 (Religious Orders)<!-- Number of priests in the diocese -->\n<!---- Current leadership ---->\n| pope              = {{Incumbent pope}} <!-- DO NOT CHANGE. This will update the Popes Automatically as they change -->\n| bishop_title      = Archbishop\n| bishop            = Giuseppe Fiorini Morosini, [[Minim (religious order)|O.M.]]\n| coadjutor         = \n| auxiliary_bishops = \n| vicar_general     = \n| emeritus_bishops  = \n<!---- Map ---->\n| map               = Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Reggio Calabria-Bova in Italy.svg\n| map_alt           = \n| map_caption       = \n<!---- Website ---->\n| website           = \n| footnotes         = \n}}\nThe '''Archdiocese of Reggio Calabria-Bova''' ({{lang-la|Archidioecesis Rheginensis-Bovensis}}) is a [[Roman Catholic]] ecclesiastical territory in [[Calabria]], southern Italy.<ref>[http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/12717a.htm Reggio di Calabria] - [[Catholic Encyclopedia]] article</ref> It received its current title in 1986, when the independent [[Diocese of Bova]] was suppressed,<ref name=CathHierReggioCala>[http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/diocese/drecb.html \"Archdiocese of Reggio Calabria-Bova\"] ''[[Catholic-Hierarchy.org]]''. David M. Cheney. Retrieved October 7, 2016</ref><ref name=GCathReggioCala>[http://www.gcatholic.org/dioceses/diocese/regg0.htm \"Metropolitan Archdiocese of Reggio Calabria\u2013Bova\"] ''GCatholic.org''. Gabriel Chow. Retrieved October 7, 2016</ref> and the territory and title of the diocese added to that of the Archdiocese of Reggio.\n\n==History==\n{{expand section|date=October 2016}}\nThrough a fanciful reading of ''The Book of Acts of the Apostles'' 27, [[Paul the Apostle|St. Paul]] was said to have preached the Gospel at Reggio Calabria, and to have consecrated his companion, [[St. Stephen]], bishop.<ref>Lanzoni, p. 337. D'Avino, p. 563.</ref> The first bishop known is Bishop [[Marcus of Calabria]], who was one of five legates of Pope Sylvester at the [[First Council of Nicaea|Council of Nicaea]] (325).<ref>J. D. Mansi, ''Sacrorum Conciliorum nova et amplissima collectio'', editio novissima [http://www.documentacatholicaomnia.eu/20vs/200_Mansi/1692-1769,_Mansi_JD,_Sacrorum_Conciliorum_Nova_Amplissima_Collectio_Vol_002,_LT.pdf Tomus II] (Florence: A. Zatta 1759), pp. 696, 702. {{cite book|author=Karl Joseph von Hefele|title=A History of the Councils of the Church: To the close of the Council of Nicea, A.D. 325|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ifECAAAAQAAJ|volume=Volume I|year=1871|publisher=T. & T. Clark|location=Edinburgh|page=271}}</ref>\n\nWhen all Southern Italy was united to the [[Patriarchate of Constantinople]],{{when|date=October 2016}} Reggio became a metropolitan see with thirteen suffragans, and followed the [[Greek Rite]], which was changed to the [[Gallican Rite]] after the Norman Conquest in the eleventh century; [[Gaspare Ricciullo del Fosso|Archbishop Ricciullo]] adopted the [[Roman Rite]] in 1580. The Greek Rite, however, continued to be used in the church of Santissima Maria della Cattolica, built by King Roger, and governed by a [[protopope]] with a numerous Greek clergy. Questions of jurisdiction caused frequent controversies with the archbishop. About 1600 Archbishop Annibale d'Afflitto suppressed the Greek Rite in that church, and the entire diocese now follows the Roman Rite.\n\nIn 1594 the city of Reggio suffered a devastating attack of the Turkish fleet, which did severe damage to churches, monasteries and hospitals.<ref>Bolani, II, p. 247</ref>\n\nIn 1783 an earthquake struck the city and damaged the Cathedral of the Assumption of the Body of the Blessed Virgin Mary into Heaven.<ref name=\"D'Avino, p. 563\">D'Avino, p. 563.</ref>\n\nOn 28 December 1908 a severe earthquake heavily damaged the Cathedral of Reggio.  Reconstruction was immediately put in motion by Archbishop Rinaldo Rousset.<ref>{{cite book|author=Giuseppe Santagata|title=Calabria sacra: compendio storico-artistico della monumentalit\u00e0 chiesastica calabrese|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KpBNAAAAYAAJ|year=1974|publisher=Parallelo 38|language=Italian|page=356}}</ref>\n\nThe Cathedral is served by a Chapter composed of four dignities and twenty four Canons.  The dignities are: the Dean, the Cantor, the Archdeacon, and the Treasurer. Originally there were only twelve Canons, but Archbishop Centelles increased the number to eighteen, and Archbishop Gaspare de Creales brought the number up to twenty-four.<ref name=\"D'Avino, p. 563\"/> Pope Benedict XIV, in a Bull of 25 September 1741, granted the Canons the right to wear a [[mitre]] and a cope.\n\n==Bishops==\n===to 1200===\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n: ? [[St. Sisinnius]] (536)<ref>A Sisinnius is mentioned in the ''Acts of [[St. Placidus]]'', written by Peter the Deacon, monk of Montecassino. Lanzoni, p. 338, calls the story of Placidus ''lavoro pienamente favoloso''.</ref>\n:'''...'''\n*Lucius<ref>Bishop Lucius was the predecessor of Bishop Bonifacius.  Lanzoni p. 339. Philipp Jaff\u00e9 and S. Loewenfeld (edd.) ''[https://archive.org/details/regestapontificu01cath Regesta pontificum romanorum]'' editio altera (Leipzig: Veit 1885), p. 157, no. 1248.</ref>\n*Bonifatius  (attested 592 \u2013 599)<ref>Knowledge of Bonifacius is based on seven letters of Pope Gregory I, written between 592 and 599. Jaff\u00e9-Loewenfeld, nos. 1208, 1248, 1276, 1389, 1465, 1586, 1655. Lanzoni, p. 339.</ref>\n*Joannes (attested 649)<ref>Bishop Giovanni was present at the Roman Synod of [[Pope Martin I]] in 649. J.-D. Mansi (ed.), ''Sacrorum Conciliorum nova et amplissima collectio'', editio novissima, [http://www.documentacatholicaomnia.eu/20vs/200_Mansi/1692-1769,_Mansi_JD,_Sacrorum_Conciliorum_Nova_Amplissima_Collectio_Vol_010,_LT.pdf Tomus X] (Florence: A. Zatta 1764), p. 867.</ref>\n:'''...'''\n*Joannes (attested 680)<ref>He was sent to Constantinople as part of an embassy from Pope Agatho to the Emperors. Kehr, p. 19, no. 10. {{cite book|author=Karl Joseph von Hefele|title=A History of the Councils of the Church, from the Original Documents|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jNNEAAAAYAAJ|volume=Volume V|year=1896|publisher=T. & T. Clark|location=Edinburgh|page=143}}</ref>\n:'''...'''\n*Constantinus (attested 790)<ref>Cappelletti, p. 157.</ref>\n:'''...'''\n*Leontius (attested 869)<ref>Leontius was present at the [[Fourth Council of Constantinople (Roman Catholic)|IV Ecumenical Council of Constantinople]].  Mansi (ed.), [http://www.documentacatholicaomnia.eu/20vs/200_Mansi/1692-1769,_Mansi_JD,_Sacrorum_Conciliorum_Nova_Amplissima_Collectio_Vol_016,_LT.pdf Tomus XVI] (Venice 1771), p. 195. A Bishop Leo is attested at the Synod of Constantinople of Patriarch Photius in 879. Ughelli, p. 324, wonders whether he might be the same person as Leontius.</ref>\n:'''...'''\n*Eusebius (c. 902 \u2013 916)<ref>Eusebius is said to have served for fourteen years, during wars against Saracens and Greek, and to have died in 916. Ughelli, p. 324. Cappelletti, p. 157.</ref>\n*Stephanus (916\u2013?)<ref>Stephanus was the successor of Eusebius and dedicated the Church of S. Michele Archangelo.  Ughelli, p. 324, Cappelletti, p. 157.</ref>\n*Galatus\n*Rogerius (attested 1014)\n:'''...'''\n*Basilius, Greek Metropolitan of Calabria (? \u2013 c. 1078)<ref>Kehr, pp. 20-21, nos. 12-13.</ref> \n*Arnulphus (c. 1081 \u2013 1090)<ref>Ughelli, p. 324.</ref>\n*Rangerius, O.S.B. (1090\u20131112)<ref>Rangerius was a French Benedictine of the Monastery of [[Marmoutier Abbey, Tours|Majoris Monasterii]] in Tours. On 5 September 1092, as Bishop of Reggio, Rangerius consecrated the church of S. Maria in the territory of the Monastery of Cava. On 10 March 1096 Rangerius co-consecrated a cemetery outside the walls of the Majoris Monasterii in Tours. Cappelletti, pp. 157-158. Kehr, p. 22, no. 16.</ref>\n:'''...'''\n*Rogerius (1146\u20131169)<ref>On 19 November 1165, Pope Alexander III confirmed for Bishop Rogerius the possessions of the diocese, as well as its metropolitan status over the dioceses of Tropea, Nicastro, Squillace, Cassana, Bova, Gerace, Oppido, and Cotrona. Kehr, p. 23, no. 20. Gams, p. 916.</ref>\n:'''...'''\n*Thomas (attested 1179 \u2013 1189)<ref>Thomas attended the Lateran Council of 1179. He died in the first half of 1190. Kamp, II, pp. 917-919.</ref>\n*Guillelmus (attested 4 October 1190 \u2013 7 April 1199, died)<ref>Kamp, p. 919-920.</ref>\n*J(acobus) (16 August 1199 \u2013 c. 1215)<ref>Jacobus had been Archdeacon. He died in the first year of [[Pope Honorius III]]. Kamp, pp. 920-921, points out that the name Jacobus is the traditional expansion of a single initial \"I\" in a subscription. Ughelli, p. 326. Eubel, I, p. 418.</ref>\n{{div col end}}\n\n===from 1200 to 1600===\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*Giraldus (attested 24 June 1215 \u2013 21 November 1216)<ref>Kamp, pp. 922-925.</ref>\n*Lando (attested July 1218 \u2013 9 February 1236)<ref>Lando was consecrated by [[Pope Gregory IX]]. Lando was transferred to the diocese of Messina on 9 February 1236. He died in 1248 or 1249. Ughelli, pp. 326-327. Eubel, I, pp. 337, 418. Kamp, pp. 926-930.</ref>\n*Vernaccio  (1252 \u2013 after 12 January 1255)<ref>Vernaccio had been Chaplain of [[Pope Innocent IV]]. He was elected by the Chapter of Reggio and confirmed by Pope Innocent in 1252. A. Potthast, ''Regesta pontificum Romanorum'' Tomus II (Berlin 1875), p. 1217, no. 14771 (13 November 1252); Ughelli, IX, p. 327. Alexander IV wrote to the Chapter, reconfirming Archbishop Vernaccio.  Bolani, p. 241. {{cite book|author=Klaus Ganzer|title=Papsttum und Bistumsbesetzungen in der Zeit von Gregor IX. bis Bonifaz VIII: ein Beitrage zur Geschichte der p\u00e4pstlichen Reservationen|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OiLSAAAAMAAJ|year=1968|publisher=B\u00f6hlau Verlag|location=K\u00f6ln|language=German|pages=196, 229}} Kamp, pp. 932-933.</ref>\n*Jacobus de Castiglione (11 March 1259 \u2013 1277)<ref>Giacomo was a relative of [[Pope Alexander IV]], and a Papal Chaplain. He was in exile from Reggio from 1259 to 1266. He died in 1277. Bolani, p. 241. Eubel, I, p. 418. Kamp, pp. 933-936.</ref>\n*Gentile, O. Min. (9 October 1279 \u2013 6 July 1307)<ref>[[Pope Nicholas III]] rejected the choice of the Cathedral Chapter, Roberto de Castellione, and appointed instead one of his familiars, Fra Gentile.  The Pope personally consecrated Gentile a bishop. Ughelli, p. 328. Cappelletti, p. 160. Eubel, I, p. 418, with note 3.</ref>\n*Tommaso (7 August 1307 \u2013 1316)<ref>Tommaso was the son of Conte Pietro de Catanzaro.  Ughelli, p. 328. Eubel, I, p. 418.</ref>\n:''Sede vacante'' (1316\u20131321)\n*Pietro, [[Order of Saint Augustine|O.S.A.]] (30 April 1321 \u2013 1328 Died)<ref>Bolani, p. 242. Eubel, I, p. 418.</ref>\n*Pietro de Galganis (5 October 1328 \u2013 29 January 1354)<ref>Galgani had been Archdeacon of Siponto. Bishop Pietro was transferred to Cosenza on 29 January 1354. Bolani, p. 242. Eubel, I, pp. 220, 418.</ref>\n*Filippo Maurello de Castiglione (29 January 1354 \u2013 c. 1363?)<ref>Filippo had been a Canon of Cosentino. Bolani, p. 242. Eubel, I, p. 418.</ref>\n*Carlo (12 February 1364 \u2013 c. 1371?)<ref>Carlo da Conte Urso held a Licentiate in Canon Law. He was appointed and consecrated by [[Pope Urban V]]. Bolani, p. 242. Eubel, I, p. 418.</ref>\n*Tommaso della Porta (19 January 1372 \u2013 ? )<ref>Thomas was a native of Salerno and a Canon of the Cathedral Chapter of Salerno; he held a Licenciate in law. Bishop Thomas had been Bishop of Teano (1369\u20131372). After appointment as Archbishop, he resided in Avignon until 1374. Bolani, p. 242. Eubel, I, pp. 418, 481.</ref>\n*Giordano (c. 1382 \u2013 1404?)<ref>On 15 October 1381 he held the office of Collector of Papal Revenues in the diocese of Reggio. Bolani, p. 242. Eubel, I, p. 418, note 7.</ref>\n*[[Pietro Filomarini]] (1404\u20131420 Died) \n*[[Bartolomeo Gattola]] (1421\u20131426) Appointed [[Archbishop of Messina]] \n*[[Gaspare Colonna]] (1426\u20131429) Appointed [[Archbishop of Benevento]] \n*[[Paolo di Segni]] (1429\u20131437 Resigned) \n*[[Guglielmo Logoteta]] (1440\u20131449 Died)<ref>Guglielmo Logoteta: Bolani, p. 243. Eubel, II, p. 222.</ref>\n*[[Angelo de Grassis]]  (30 April 1449 \u2013 1453 Died)<ref>Grassis had been Archdeacon of Siponto, and Bishop of Ariano (1433\u20131449).  He was appointed to Reggio by [[Pope Nicholas V]]. Bolani, p. 243. Eubel, II, pp. 94, 222.</ref>\n*[[Antonio Ricci (archbishop of Reggio Calabria)|Antonio Ricci]] (4 June 1453 \u2013 1488 Died)<ref>Ricci: Bolani, p. 243. Eubel, II, p. 222.</ref> \n:''Sede vacante'' (1488\u20131491)\n*[[Marco Miroldi]], [[Order of Preachers|O.P.]] (4 January 1491 \u2013 1495 Died)<ref>Miroldi: Bolani, p. 243-244. Eubel, II, pp. 94, 222</ref> \n*[[Pietro Isvales]] (1497\u201324 Jul 1506 Resigned)\n*[[Francesco Isvales]] (1506\u20131512 Died)<ref>Francesco Isvales: Bolani, p. 244. Eubel, III, p. 284.</ref>\n*[[Roberto Latino Orsini]] (23 July 1512 \u2013 1520 Resigned)<ref>Orsini: Bolani, p. 244. Eubel, III, p. 284.</ref>\n*[[Agostino Trivulzio]] (24 August 1520 \u2013 1 October 1520 Resigned), Administrator\n*[[Pietro Trivulzio]] (1 October 1520 \u2013 1523 Died)<ref>Pietro Trivulzio: Bolani, pp. 244-245. Eubel, III, p. 284</ref>\n*[[Agostino Trivulzio]] (26 November 1523 \u2013 16 July 1529 Resigned), Administrator\n*[[Girolamo Centelles]] (16 July 1529 \u2013 1535 Resigned)<ref>Bolani, II, p. 245. Eubel, III, p. 284.</ref>\n*[[Agostino Gonzaga]] (11 April 1537 \u2013 1557 Died)<ref>Agostino Gonzaga was a native of Mantua. He was nominated Archbishop of Reggio by Emperor Charles V, and confirmed by Pope Paul III on 11 April 1537. Bolani, p. 245. Eubel, III, p. 284.</ref> \n*[[Gaspare Ricciullo del Fosso]], [[Order of the Minims|O.M.]] (1560\u20131592 Died)<ref name=CathHierGaspRicc>[http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/bishop/bfossag.html \"Archbishop Gaspare Ricciullo del Fosso, O.M.\"] ''[[Catholic-Hierarchy.org]]''. David M. Cheney. Retrieved October 17, 2016. [http://www.gcatholic.org/dioceses/diocese/regg0.htm#41889 \"Archbishop Gaspare Ricciullo Del Fosso, O.M.\"] ''GCatholic.org''. Gabriel Chow. Retrieved October 7, 2016. Bolani, II, pp. 245-246.</ref>\n*[[Annibale D'Afflitto]] (15 November 1593 \u2013 1 April 1638 Died)<ref>D'Afflitto was a native of Palermo. He studied law in Rome, but took his degree ''in utroque iure'' (Civil and Canon Law) in Padua. He joined the Court of King Philip II. He was appointed Archbishop of Reggio by [[Pope Clement VIII]] when not yet thirty-five years old.  He was consecrated by Cardinal Alfonso Gesualdo, Bishop of Ostia e Velletri, on 30 November 1593. He took possession of his diocese on 7 September 1594.  He restored and decorated the cathedral. He held a synod, attended by the Bishops of Nicoteri, Mileto, Tropea, Bova, and Gerace, along with representatives of other dioceses and institutions. He died on Holy Thursday, 1 April 1638. Ughelli, pp. 336-337. Gauchat, ''Hierarchia catholica''. IV, p. 294, with note 2.</ref>\n{{div col end}}\n\n===from 1600 to 1900===\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n:''Sede vacante'' (1638 \u2013 1644)\n*[[Gaspar de Creales Arce]] (12 December 1644 \u2013 1658 Died)<ref>Cereales y Arce: Ughelli, p. 337. Gauchat, IV, p. 294, with note 3.</ref>\n*[[Matteo di G\u00e9nnaro]] (5 April 1660 \u2013 21 January 1674 Died)<ref>Gennaro was born in Naples, and was a ''Doctor in utroque iure'' (Civil and Canon Law) from the University of Naples.  He was Primicerius of the Cathedral of Naples. Ughelli, pp. 336-337. Gauchat, Hierarchia catholica. IV, p. 294, with note 4. Ritzler-Sefrin, V, p. 332 note 2.</ref>\n*[[Mart\u00edn Ib\u00e1\u00f1ez y Villanueva]], [[O.SS.T.]] (27 May 1675 \u2013 September 1695 Died)<ref>Martinus de Villanueva had previously been Bishop of Gaeta (1670\u20131675). Ughelli, p. 338. Ritzler-Sefrin, V, pp. 135; 332 with note 3.</ref>\n*[[Giovanni Andrea Monreale]] (1696\u20131726 Died)<ref>Monreale: Ritzler-Sefrin, V, p. 332 with note 4.</ref>\n*Domingo (Damiano) Polou (1727\u20131756 Died)<ref>Polou: Ritzler-Sefrin, V, p. 332 with note 5.</ref>\n*Domenico Zicari (1757\u20131760 Died)<ref>Zicari: Ritzler-Sefrin, VI, p. 356 with note 2.</ref>\n*Matteo Gennaro Testa Piccolomini (1761\u20131766 Resigned)<ref>Testa: Ritzler-Sefrin, VI, p. 356 with note 3.</ref>\n*Alberto Maria (Leonardo Antonio Pasquale) Capobianco, [[Order of Preachers|O.P.]] (1767\u20131792 Resigned)<ref>Capobianco: Ritzler-Sefrin, VI, p. 356 with note 4.</ref> \n*Giuseppe Maria Cenicela, [[O.F.M. Disc.]] (1797\u20131814 Died)<ref>In religious life, Cenicela's name was Bernardo of the Immaculate Conception. Ritzler-Sefrin, VI, p. 356 with note 5. Taccone-Gallucci, p. 401.</ref>\n:''Sede vacante'' (1814\u20131818)\n* Alessandro Tommasini (1818\u20131826 Died)<ref>Tommasini had been Provost of Reggio, and then Bishop of Oppido (1792\u20131818). He held a diocesan synod in Reggio in 1823. Taccone-Gallucci, p. 401. Gams, p. 909.</ref>\n* Emanuele Maria Bellorado, [[Order of Preachers|O.P.]] (28 January 1828 \u2013 18 May 1829)<ref>Bellorado had previously been Bishop of Catanzaro (1824\u20131828). He became Bishop of Acerra and [[Bishop of Sant'Agata de' Goti|S. Agata de' Goti]] (1829 - 1833). Gams, pp. 846, 874. Taccone-Gallucci, p. 401.</ref>\n* Leone Ciampa, [[O.F.M. Disc.]] (18 May 1829 \u2013 1 February 1836)<ref>Born in Serracapriola in 1782, Ciampa had been lector in theology for his Order, and Provincial of the Alcantarine branch of the [[Franciscans]] before his appointment as Archbishop. He was transferred to the diocese of [[Archbishop of Conza e Campagna|Conza]]) (1 February 1836 \u2013 22 December 1848), and then to Sorrento (1848\u20131854). Gams, pp. 878, 917, 926. Taccone-Gallucci, p. 401.</ref>\n* Pietro di Benedetto (1836\u20131855 Died)<ref>Di Benedetto was born in Cassano in 1868. He was ordained a priest for the diocese of Cassano. He held the degree ''Doctor in utroque iure'' (Civil and Canon Law). He had been Archdeacon of Cassano, and was Capitular Vicar, Theologian, and Penitentiary. He was named Archbishop on 11 July 1836. ''Annuario Pontificio 1838'', p. 152. Taccone-Gallucci, pp. 401-402.</ref>\n* Mariano Ricciardi (1855\u20131871)<ref>Ricciardi was a native of Naples. Ricciardi was in Rome for the [[First Vatican Council|I Vatican Council]] (1869\u20131870), and after the annexation of the [[Kingdom of Naples]] to the [[Kingdom of Italy]] in 1870, he was unable or unwilling to return. He was instead appointed [[Archbishop of Sorrento]] by [[Pope Pius IX]]. He died in 1875. {{cite book|title=La Scienza e la fede|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RKFCAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA351|series=Serie quarto, Vol. 3|volume=Anno 36|year=1876|publisher=Manfredi|location=Naples|language=Italian|pages=345\u2013352, at 350}} Taccone-Gallucci, p. 402.</ref>\n* Francesco Saverio Basile (1871\u20131871 Died)<ref>Basile died before he could be consecrated.  Taccone-Gallucci, p. 402.</ref>\n* Francesco Converti, [[Order of Friars Minor|O.F.M.]] (1872\u20131888 Resigned)<ref>Converti was born in Amendolara, on the Gulf of Taranto. Taccone-Gallucci, p. 402.</ref><ref name=CathHierReggioCala />\n* Gennaro Portanova (1888\u20131908 Died)<ref>Portanova was born in Naples in 1845.  He was Coadjutor and then Bishop of Ischia from 1885 to 1888. He was named a cardinal by [[Pope Leo XIII]] on 19 June 1899. Taccone-Gallucci, p. 402. {{cite book|author=Martin Br\u00e4uer|title=Handbuch der Kardin\u00e4le: 1846-2012|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=363pBQAAQBAJ|year=2014|publisher=De Gruyter|location=Berlin|language=German|isbn=978-3-11-026947-5|page=184}}Salvador Miranda, ''The Cardinals of the Holy Roman Church'', [http://www2.fiu.edu/~mirandas/bios1899.htm#Portanova ''Portanova, Gennaro''], retrieved: 2017-02-22.</ref>\n{{div col end}}\n\n===since 1900===\n[[File:Mons Giuseppe Fiorini Morosini.JPG|thumb|right|150px|Archbishop Morosini]]\n*Rinaldo Camillo Rousset, [[O.C.D.]] (1909\u20131926 Died)<ref>Rousset was born in Beaulard (diocese of Susa, Province of Trent) in 1860. He was Procurator General of his Order in 1893, and Superior General in 1901. He was an Examiner of Clergy in the diocese of Rome, and a Consultor of the SC of Bishops and Regulars (1905). He was previously Bishop of Bagnorea (1906\u20131909), appointed by [[Pope Pius X]] on 21 February 1906; he was consecrated a bishop on 30 December 1906 by Cardinal Girolamo Gotti. He was nominated Archbishop of Reggio on 18 September 1909. Rousset died on 26 May 1926. A. Battandier (ed.), ''Annuaire pontifical catholique'' (Paris 1908), p. 179. ''Annuario pontificio 1922'', p. 203.</ref> \n*Carmelo Pujia  (1927\u20131937 Died)<ref>Pujia was a native of Filadelfia (diocese of Mileto). He was Bishop of Anglona e Tursi (1897\u20131905). Pujia was nominated Archbishop of Santa Severina by royal decree of 15 October 1905, and approved by Pope Pius X in a bull of 8 November 1905. From 1920 to 1922 Pujia was Apostolic Administrator of the diocese of Cotrone. {{cite book|title=Bollettino ufficiale del Ministero di Grazia, Giustizia e dei Culti|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=B7FKAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA59|volume=Volume 27|year=1907|publisher=Stamperia reale|location=Rome|language=Italian|page=59}} A. Battandier (ed.), ''Annuaire pontifical catholique 1908'', p. 259.</ref> \n*Enrico Montalbetti, [[Obs. S.C.]] (1938\u20131943 Died) \n*Antonio Lanza (1943\u20131950 Died) \n*[[Giovanni Ferro]], [[C.R.S.]] (1950\u20131977 Retired) \n*Aureliano Sorrentino (1977\u20131990 Retired) \n*Vittorio Luigi Mondello (1990\u20132013 Retired) \n*Giuseppe Fiorini Morosini, [[Order of the Minims|O.M.]] (2013\u2013 )<ref>Morosini was born at Paola (diocese of Cosenza-Bisignano) on 27 November 1945. He studied at the Lateran University in Rome, taking a doctorate in theology in 1970; he also studied at the University of Messina, taking a doctorate in philosophy in 1975.  He was Director of the Third Order of Minims (1983\u20131992), as well as Corrector Provinciale at Paola (1986\u20131992).  From 1992 to 1994 he was Corrector of the new house of the Minims in Vranov in the Czech Republic. He was Corrector General (Superior) of the Minims from 1994 to 2006. Morosini was named Bishop of Locri on 20 March 2008, and consecrated in Rome on 9 May 2008 by Cardinal Renato Martino. He was transferred to Reggio on 13 July 2013. He is a member of the Episcopal Commission for the Evangelization of Peoples. ''Archdiocesi di Reggio Calabria\u2013Bova'', [http://www.reggiobova.it/index.php/arcivescovo/biografia Giuseppe Fiorini Morosini], retrieved: 2017-02-22.</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n===Reference works===\n*{{cite book|last=Gams|first=Pius Bonifatius |title=Series episcoporum Ecclesiae catholicae: quotquot innotuerunt a beato Petro apostolo|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=os9DAQAAMAAJ|year=1873|publisher=Typis et Sumptibus Georgii Josephi Manz|location=Ratisbon}} p.&nbsp;926-917. (Use with caution; obsolete)\n*{{cite book|last1=Eubel|first1=Conradus (ed.)|title=Hierarchia catholica, Tomus 1|date=1913|publisher=Libreria Regensbergiana|location=M\u00fcnster|edition=second|url=https://archive.org/details/hierarchiacathol01eubeuoft}}  p.&nbsp;418. (in Latin)\n*{{cite book|last1=Eubel|first1=Conradus (ed.)|title=Hierarchia catholica, Tomus 2|date=1914|publisher=Libreria Regensbergiana|location=M\u00fcnster|edition=second|url=https://archive.org/details/hierarchiacathol02eubeuoft}} p.&nbsp;222.\n*{{cite book|last1=Eubel|first1=Conradus (ed.)|last2=Gulik|first2=Guilelmus|title=Hierarchia catholica, Tomus 3|date=1923|publisher=Libreria Regensbergiana|location=M\u00fcnster|edition=second|url=https://archive.org/details/hierarchiacathol02eubeuoft}} pp.&nbsp;284.\n*{{cite book|last1=Gauchat|first1=Patritius (Patrice)|title=Hierarchia catholica IV (1592-1667)|date=1935|publisher=Libraria Regensbergiana|location=M\u00fcnster|url=https://archive.org/details/hierarchiacathol04eubeuoft|accessdate=2016-07-06}} p.&nbsp;294.\n*{{cite book|last1=Ritzler|first1=Remigius|last2=Sefrin|first2=Pirminus|title=Hierarchia catholica medii et recentis aevi V (1667-1730)|date=1952|publisher=Messagero di S. Antonio|location=Patavii|url=https://archive.org/details/hierarchiacathol05eubeuoft|accessdate=2016-07-06}} p.&nbs